# Core conventions

This rule is always applied. It is the shortest set of operating
principles for any engineer using Cursor on this hack9 project. The full
operating manual is in [AGENTS.md](mdc:AGENTS.md); read it before any
non-trivial change.

## Hackathon mode

- Speed beats polish. Ship the demo win condition first.
- Cosmetic concerns and refactors are deferred to `TODO.md`, not done
  inline.
- The 4-hour cap is sacred. After the 3:00 elapsed mark, no new
  features — polish only.

## Workflow contract

- Every change ships as a PR. Open with `gh pr create`. Do not push to
  `main` directly. Only P1 merges to `main`.
- Branch names: `feat/<short-kebab>`, `spike/<short-kebab>`,
  `fix/<short-kebab>`.
- For parallel work, use git worktrees via the
  [.cursor/commands/spike.md](mdc:.cursor/commands/spike.md) flow or
  `bash scripts/spike.sh <name>`.

## Code citations

When discussing code in chat, cite specific locations with
`path:line` (e.g. `lib/db/schema.ts:42`). Do not paraphrase code
without citing.

## Security

- Never commit secrets. Use `.env.local` for runtime values and
  `.env.example` for the public schema.
- Anything matching `id_rsa`, `id_ed25519`, `*.pem` is off-limits.
- The hooks in [.cursor/hooks.json](mdc:.cursor/hooks.json) and the
  `/pr-merge` gate at [.cursor/commands/pr-merge.md](mdc:.cursor/commands/pr-merge.md)
  enforce parts of this; do not work around them.

## Definition of Done

A change is ready to ship when [AGENTS.md §5](mdc:AGENTS.md) Definition
of Done holds. The short form:

1. `pnpm typecheck` clean (or absent in Phase 1)
2. Tests pass for changed modules
3. Screenshot in PR body for UI changes
4. Reviewer report says `OK_TO_MERGE: yes`
5. No secrets added
6. One-sentence "what + why" at the top of the PR body
